1285","ABT 1227":"about 1227","1293":"1293","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, , England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Colmworth, Bedford, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Weldebof was born about 1227, in Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Walter Weldebof, was 28 and her mother, Isabel, was 23. She married John de Braybrooke. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1302, in her hometown."},"et":{"ABT 1227–AFT 1302":"umbes 1227–pärast 1302","1227–1302":"1227–1302","1220–1293":"1220–1293","1264–1324":"1264–1324","1201–Male":"1201–Surnud","1205–1285":"1205–1285","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1324":"1324","1302":"1302","AFT 1302":"pärast 1302","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","ABT 1227":"umbes 1227","1293":"1293","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, , England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colmworth, Bedford, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1227–AFT 1302":"noin 1227–1302 jälkeen","1227–1302":"1227–1302","1220–1293":"1220–1293","1264–1324":"1264–1324","1201–Male":"1201–Kuollut","1205–1285":"1205–1285","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1324":"1324","1302":"1302","AFT 1302":"1302 jälkeen","1201":"1201","1222":"1222","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","ABT 1227":"noin 1227","1293":"1293","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, , England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Colmworth, Bedford, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, England":"Braybrooke, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1227–AFT 1302":"environ 1227–après 1302","1227–1302":"1227–1302","1220–1293":"1220–1293","1264–1324":"1264–1324","1201–Male":"1201–Décédé","1205–1285":"